fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let s \colon  B \to  A and r \colon  A \to  B be a pair of maps. A homotopy h \colon  r\circ  s \sim  1_{B} exhibits s as a section of r and r as a retraction of s. Together, 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen s,r\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 are referred to as a section-retraction pair.

Let \mathcal {A} be a path object, and let B\colon    \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {} \to  \mathsf {Prop} be a family of propositions. Then the reflexive subgraph comprehension 
 \mathopen {}\left \lbrace x:\mathcal {A}\,\middle \vert \,B  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x\right \rparen \mathclose {} \right \rbrace \mathclose {}
 is a path object.

A suitable path object on sections to a fixed function r\colon  A \to  B is given by a contravariant sum of path objects \mathchoice {\textstyle \int _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen s:\mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}\mathord {\vartriangle }A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \int _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen s:\mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}\mathord {\vartriangle }A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \int _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen s:\mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}\mathord {\vartriangle }A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \int _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen s:\mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}\mathord {\vartriangle }A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}r\circ  s \sim  1_{B}, as sectionhood witnesses form a right-cloven family over their underlying sections (). In particular, an isomorphism of sections of r from 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen s,h\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 to 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen s',h'\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 is given by a homotopy H_s \colon  s \sim  s' together with a higher homotopy H_h \colon  h \sim    \mathopen {}\left \lparen \lambda {x}\mathpunct {.}\mathsf {act}_{r}  \mathopen {}\left \lparen H_s x\right \rparen \mathclose {} \cdot  h'x\right \rparen \mathclose {} .

A suitable path object on retractions to a fixed function s\colon  B \to  A is given by a contravariant sum of path objects  \mathchoice {\textstyle \int _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen r:\mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}\mathord {\vartriangle }B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \int _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen r:\mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}\mathord {\vartriangle }B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \int _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen r:\mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}\mathord {\vartriangle }B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \int _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen r:\mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}\mathord {\vartriangle }B\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}r\circ  s \sim  1_{B}, as retractionhood witnesses form a right-cloven family over their underlying sections (). In particular, an isomorphism of retractions of s from 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen r,h\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 to 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen r',h'\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 is given by a homotopy H_r \colon  r \sim  r' together with a higher homotopy H_h \colon  h \sim    \mathopen {}\left \lparen \lambda {x}\mathpunct {.}H_r  \mathopen {}\left \lparen r x\right \rparen \mathclose {} \cdot  h'x\right \rparen \mathclose {} .

We fix pairs 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen a,b\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 and 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen a',b'\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 in \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \sum _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \sum _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{Bx}. By  via , it suffices to exhibit identifications p\colon  a = a' and q\colon  p_* b = b'. These are given respectively by our assumptions that A and Ba' are propositions.

Let a_0 be the centre of contraction of A and let b_0 be the centre of contraction of Ba_0. Then we let the centre of contraction of \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \sum _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \sum _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}Bx be 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen a_0,b_0\right \rparen \mathclose {}
. The necessary identifications are obtained from the contractibility of A and Ba_0 by the characterisation of identifications in dependent sums (, ).

Suppose we have two centres of contraction a,a':A with \chi _\bullet \colon  \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}a = x and \chi '_\bullet \colon \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}a'=x as witnesses of contraction. To identify 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen a,\chi _\bullet \right \rparen \mathclose {}
 with 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen a',\chi '_\bullet \right \rparen \mathclose {}
, we employ the covariant sum of each of the pointwise path object structures on \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}-=x over the intrinsic path object structure on A, constructing an identification p\colon  a = a' followed by a homotopy H \colon    \mathopen {}\left \lparen   \mathopen {}\left \lparen \chi _{a'}\right \rparen \mathclose {} _*^{\mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}-=x} \chi _\bullet \right \rparen \mathclose {}  \sim  \chi '_\bullet . Fixing z\colon  A, we compute:

Let \epsilon  \colon  f\circ  f^{-1} = 1_{B} be the counit of the inverse to f\colon  A\to  B. Given b:B, we must show that the fiber of f over b is contractible; the centre of contraction is given by the pair 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen f^{-1} x, \epsilon  x\right \rparen \mathclose {}
, and the required paths can be constructed via the univalence principle for fibers using the unit \eta \colon  f^{-1}\circ  f = 1_{A}, the coherence \chi \colon  \mathsf {act}_{f}\circ \eta \sim \epsilon \circ  f, and the naturality of homotopies.

As f is an embedding, the map \mathsf {act}_{f}\colon  a_0 = a_1 \to  fa_0 = fa_1 has an inverse 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \mathsf {act}_{f}^{-1},\epsilon ,\eta ,\chi \right \rparen \mathclose {}
.

Given a function f\colon  A\to  B and a section g\colon  B\to  A witnessed by \epsilon \colon  f\circ  g = 1_{B}, we define the coherent remainder of 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\epsilon \right \rparen \mathclose {}
 to be the following sum:

Given elements 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \eta _0,\chi _0\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 and 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \eta _1,\chi _1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 of \mathsf {coherentRemainder}_{f}\sigma , the resulting type   \mathopen {}\left \lparen \eta _0,\chi _0\right \rparen \mathclose {} \cong _{\mathsf {coherentRemainder}_{f}\sigma }  \mathopen {}\left \lparen \eta _1,\chi _1\right \rparen \mathclose {}  is definitionally equivalent to the following dependent sum:

Without loss of generality, we may assume that f has an inverse 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\epsilon ,\eta ,\chi \right \rparen \mathclose {}
. By , it suffices to argue that the type of inverses to f is a retract of a proposition; the type of inverses to f is in fact equivalent to the type of sections equipped with a coherent remainder:

By , it suffices to show that the type of sections to f is a proposition and that for every such section, the coherent remainder thereof is a proposition. The latter is , and the former follows from  by means of the retraction 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g,\eta \right \rparen \mathclose {}
.

By the univalence principle for types, we may contract 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen D_0,F_0\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 to 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen   \mathopen {}\left \lvert C\right \rvert \mathclose {} , 1_{  \mathopen {}\left \lvert C\right \rvert \mathclose {} }\right \rparen \mathclose {}
:

